    <div class="ans111">
  <div class="column left">
   <h2>Compiler</h2>
   <ol>
<li>Translation: Translates the whole program at once into an intermediate object code/machine code. </li>
<li>Execution: Faster, as translation happens beforehand, producing a native executable. </li>
<li>Error Handling: Reports all syntax errors after scanning the entire code.</li>
<li>Portability: Less portable; compiled code is specific to the target machine architecture. </li>
<li>Examples: C, C++, Rust. </li>
</ol>
  </div>
  <div class="column right">
 <h2>Interpreter</h2>
<ol>
    <li>Translation: Translates and executes one line or statement at a time.</li>
    <li>Execution: Slower, as translation and execution overlap.</li>
    <li>Error Handling: Reports errors line-by-line as they are encountered.</li>
    <li>Portability: Highly portable; the same source code runs on any system with the interpreter.</li>
    <li>Examples: Python, JavaScript, Ruby (though Python uses bytecode too)</li>
</ol>
  </div>

    </div>

